    en: "New York Tax Law Section 173 authorizes the NYS Commissioner of Taxation and Finance to file a 'tax warrant' against a taxpayer owing back state taxes. Filed in the County Clerk's office, the warrant creates a judgment-like lien on the taxpayer's real and personal property in the county — like a civil judgment, it clouds title and enables enforcement tools (wage garnishment, bank levy, property seizure). The warrant is public record and shows on credit reports. A taxpayer can resolve a warrant by (1) paying the tax in full, (2) entering an Installment Payment Agreement (IPA) under Tax Law 171, or (3) negotiating an Offer in Compromise under Tax Law 171(18-a). Once paid, the warrant is satisfied and released, but the historical filing remains searchable."
